notesStmt.note: A prayer, to be said four times in the morning and the evening, has been inscribed on the last flyleaf verso by a later owner.

msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: Copy of a set of works on Islamic theology and ritual practice written in Tashelhit (Shilha) in Arabic letters. Several leaves of the first work have been rewritten by a different copyist on smaller paper; the last work is missing the conclusion and the last few lines of the chapter. The works were composed in the early 18th century, between 1707 and 1714.

supportDesc.extent: 189 leaves : 230 x 170 (170 x 90) mm bound to 235 x 187 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Contemporary foliation in Western Arabic numerals in black ink, upper left recto (unnumbered, 4-100; 1[00]-[1]32). Modern foliation added in pencil to continue the sequence, upper left recto (133-164). A loose quire of 4 bifolia on machine-made paper, paginated (1-7), is laid in at the front of the copy. The first few leaves of the copy are damaged around the edges; the number is missing from one. Catchwords every verso, lower left, perpendicular to text.

layoutDesc.layout: Chiefly 19 long lines; loose quire in 14 long lines.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in maghribi in brown ink; pointed, vocalized.

binding.p: Bound in reddish brown leather over pasteboard with flap (Type II). Embossed paper onlay central mandorla and blind tooled intersecting lines and frame on both covers and flap.

origin.p: Likely copied in Morocco in the second half of the 18th or first half of the 19th century.

history.provenance: Acquired by Talcott Williams on an expedition to Morocco for the Department of Archaeology and Paleontology at the University of Pennsylvania, June 26, 1897 (memorandum laid in).
